page.title: 19Humphrey Head
page.content: Two miles south of Allithwaite is {Humphrey Head,a limestone headland, extending out into{Morecambe Bay. It is a beautiful area,steep cliffs on the west side,slope down eastwards into lovely woodlands.The area abounds with wildlife,there is a rich flora, the surrounding fields and mud-flats are a haven for thousands of birds.The head is a{Site of Special Scientific {Interest. Humphrey Head is a popular place for naturalists,geologists,botanists and walkers.There is a residential centre, owned by North Yorkshire C.C.,for out- door education. The headland gets it's name from an early Angle settler,Hunfrith.There is a 'Holy Well' of mineral spring water, that is supposed to have medicinal properties.Legend has it that the last wolf in England was killed here.
